Lab 2: Basic R

Lets get more comfortable writing R code and documenting our results.

As you have seen in lecture, well be using RMarkdown files almost exclusively. There are several options when creating a new file in RStudio, but I find that RMarkdown files are the best when starting out. One of the reasons being that you can have both nice-looking text (regular, markdown, latex) and code in the same document. This is especially convenient for collaborating with others and making your work as reproducible as possible.

Lets look at a few R and plotting examples. Be sure to include text answers where appropriate.

Recall the murders dataset from class. Using a scatterplot of total murders versus population we saw evidence of a strong relationship: states with larger populations had more murders.

library(dplyr)
library(dslabs)
data(murders)
population_in_millions <- murders$population/10^6
total_gun_murders <- murders$total
plot(population_in_millions, total_gun_murders)

Note that many states have populations below 5 million and are bunched up. We may gain further insights from making this plot in the log scale.

  1. Transform the variables using the log10 transformation and then plot them. What do you notice?
log_pop <- log10(murders$population/10^6)
log_murders <- log10(murders$total)
plot(log_pop, log_murders)

The bunched up points in the previous plot are now more spread out and easier to see.

  1. Create a histogram of the state populations. Is it symmetric, left-skewed or right-skewed?
hist(murders$population)

It is right-skewed. This makes sense since only a few states have large populations.

  1. Generate boxplots of the state populations by region. Are there any outliers? Which region has the largest median population?
boxplot(population ~ region, data = murders)

Yes, there are outliers in the South and West regions. The North Central region has the largest median population.

Now lets practice writing our own functions - an invaluable skill for a data scientist.

  1. Create a function sum_n that for any given value, say \(n\), computes the sum of the integers from 1 to n (inclusive). Use the function to determine the sum of integers from 1 to 5,000.
sum_n <- function(n) {
    x <- 1:n
    sum(x)
}
sum_n(5000)
## [1] 12502500
  1. Create a function altman_plot that takes two arguments x and y and plots the difference against the sum.
altman_plot <- function(x, y) {
    diff_xy <- x - y
    sum_xy <- x + y
    plot(sum_xy, diff_xy, main = "Altman Plot of X and Y",
    xlab = "X + Y", ylab = "X - Y")
}
x <- 1:10
y <- x * 2
altman_plot(x, y)

  1. After running the code below, what is the value of x?
x <- 3
my_func <- function(y){
    x <- 5
    y + 5
}

Still 3. First, we just defined my_func but did not run it, so anything inside the curly braces would not be executed until we called my_func using my_func(2) (pass in any number for y).

Further, even if we ran my_func, the x inside the function does not affect the value of x outside the function, nor is it visible outside the function. In computer science terms, we say that the scope of the x inside the function is only within the set of curly braces. Therefore, when we execute x after executing my_func(2), the value printed is still 3.

x <- 3
my_func <- function(y){
    x <- 5
    y + 5
}
x
## [1] 3
my_func(2)
## [1] 7
x
## [1] 3
  1. Write a function compute_s_n that for any given \(n\) computes the sum \(S_n = 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + \dots + n^2\). Report the value of the sum when \(n=10\).
compute_s_n <- function(n) {
    x <- 1:n
    sum(x^2)
}
compute_s_n(10)
## [1] 385
  1. Now define an empty numerical vector s_n of size 25 using s_n <- vector("numeric", 25) and store in the results of \(S_1, S_2, \dots S_{25}\).
s_n <- vector("numeric", 25)
for (i in 1:25) {
    s_n[i] <- compute_s_n(i)
}
  1. Plot \(S_n\) versus \(n\). Use points defined by \(n = 1,\dots, 25\).
n <- 1:25
plot(n, s_n)

  1. Confirm that the formula for this sum is \(S_n = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}\) by adding an appropriate line to the plot above.
plot(n, s_n)
lines(n, n * (n + 1) * (2 * n + 1) / 6)
